## Part 2: Strategic Research Gaps (The Angles You're Missing)\
\
### 2.1 The Two-Sided Workflow Blind Spot\
**What you're researching**: DJ pain points (outreach, follow-ups, organization).  \
**What you're missing**: Promoter behavior and incentives.\
\
**Why this matters**: Booking isn't a solo workflow \'97 it's a *negotiation*. If promoters don't respond to structured outreach, or prefer DMs/WhatsApp over "professional" pipelines, your tool solves only half the equation.\
\
**Research to run this week**:\
- Interview 10-15 promoters/bookers: "What's your actual process for evaluating DJ inquiries? What makes you reply vs. archive?"\
- Map the *promoter's* decision tree: What signals do they look for? What friction kills a reply?\
- Test a hypothesis: Does a "promoter-friendly" outreach template (short, mobile-optimized, EPK-attached) increase reply rates vs. a "professional" long-form message?\
\
**Commercial impact**: If you discover promoters ignore "CRM-style" outreach, you pivot NoxReach to *optimize for promoter response*, not just DJ organization. That becomes your defensible wedge.\
\
> *Source insight*: "Successful DJs are no longer managing bookings through inbox searches, text messages, and handwritten notes" \'97 but this assumes promoters *want* structured systems. Validate that assumption.\
\
### 2.2 The Substitution Research Gap\
**What you're researching**: Direct competitors (other DJ CRMs).  \
**What you're missing**: What DJs *actually use today* and why they stick with it.\
\
**Why this matters**: Your real competitor isn't SupaBook or Harpsen. It's:\
- A Notion template + Google Calendar + Instagram DMs\
- A spreadsheet + manual reminders\
- "I just remember to follow up"\
\
If your tool doesn't beat *that* on effort, not just features, conversion stalls.\
\
**Research to run**:\
- "Jobs-to-be-Done" interviews: "Walk me through the last time you booked a gig. What tools did you touch? Where did you feel friction?"\
- Switching cost audit: "What would you have to stop doing, start doing, or migrate to try NoxReach?"\
- Feature parity check: Build a Notion template that replicates your core flow. If it takes <30 minutes, your moat is UX, not functionality.\
\
**Commercial impact**: If substitution is easy, you compete on *habit formation*, not features. That changes your onboarding, pricing, and retention strategy.\
\
### 2.3 The Pricing Psychology Blind Spot\
**What you're researching**: "Is \'8019/month reasonable?"  \
**What you're missing**: What DJs *anchor value against* and what outcome justifies payment.\
\
**Why this matters**: \'8019/month feels expensive if anchored to "free spreadsheet." It feels trivial if anchored to "one lost gig = \'80500."\
\
**Research to run**:\
- Van Westendorp price sensitivity survey: "At what price would NoxReach be too cheap to trust? Too expensive to consider?"\
- ROI framing test: "If NoxReach helped you book 1 extra gig per year, what would that be worth to you?"\
- Tier perception audit: Show your Free/Pro tiers to 20 DJs. Ask: "What would make you upgrade *tomorrow*?"\
\
**Commercial impact**: If you discover DJs anchor to *gig value*, not *tool cost*, you reframe pricing as "insurance against lost bookings" \'97 not "monthly software fee."\
\
> *Source insight*: Micro-SaaS pricing works best when anchored to tangible outcomes, not abstract features.\
\
### 2.4 The Retention Driver Gap\
**What you're researching**: "Will they sign up?"  \
**What you're missing**: "Will they still care in 60 days?"\
\
**Why this matters**: Early-stage SaaS lives or dies by activation and retention, not just acquisition. If DJs sign up but don't experience a "booking win" fast, churn follows.\
\
**Research to run**:\
- Activation audit: Track time-to-first-follow-up, time-to-first-reply, time-to-first-booking for new users.\
- "Aha moment" identification: What specific action correlates with 90-day retention? (e.g., "Users who send 5+ outreach messages in week 1 retain 3x longer")\
- Churn interview protocol: "What almost made you cancel? What would have kept you?"\
\
**Commercial impact**: If you discover the "aha moment" is *getting a promoter reply* (not just organizing leads), you redesign onboarding to drive that outcome faster.\
\
### 2.5 The Channel Discovery Blind Spot\
**What you're researching**: "Where should I advertise?"  \
**What you're missing**: Where DJs *actually discover tools* and who they trust for recommendations.\
\
**Why this matters**: If your CAC is high because you're advertising where DJs aren't looking, growth stalls regardless of landing page quality.\
\
**Research to run**:\
- Attribution survey: "How did you discover the last tool you started using for your DJ business?"\
- Influencer mapping: Who do DJs follow for business advice? (Not music \'97 *business*: label owners, booking agents, successful peers)\
- Community audit: Where do DJs discuss workflow? (Reddit r/Beatmatch, Discord servers, Instagram comment sections, label newsletters)\
\
**Commercial impact**: If you discover DJs trust peer recommendations over ads, you shift budget to affiliate/ambassador programs, not performance marketing.\
\
> *Source insight*: "Higher conversion rates are more realistic in niche markets" when distribution aligns with community trust.\
\
### 2.6 The Data Moat Question\
**What you're researching**: "What features should I build next?"  \
**What you're missing**: "What data could NoxReach collect that becomes defensible over time?"\
\
**Why this matters**: If your value is purely UX ("nicer pipeline"), a competitor can copy it. If your value is *network data* ("we know which Berlin promoters reply fastest to Tech-House DJs"), that compounds.\
\
**Research to run**:\
- Data inventory: What could NoxReach learn from aggregated, anonymized user behavior? (Reply rates by genre/region, optimal follow-up timing, promoter response patterns)\
- Moat hypothesis testing: "If we could tell users 'Promoters in Amsterdam reply 3x faster to messages sent Tuesday mornings,' would that be valuable enough to retain them?"\
- Privacy/ethics audit: What data can you collect *without* violating trust? How do you communicate value exchange?\
\
**Commercial impact**: If you validate a data moat, you shift roadmap from "more features" to "more insights" \'97 and pricing from "per user" to "per insight."\
\
### 2.7 The "Job Expansion" Opportunity\
**What you're researching**: "How do we get DJs to book more gigs?"  \
**What you're missing**: "What adjacent jobs do DJs need that we could own?"\
\
**Why this matters**: If NoxReach solves *only* outreach follow-ups, TAM is limited. If it becomes the "operating system for a DJ career," expansion revenue follows.\
\
**Research to run**:\
- Workflow adjacency map: What tasks do DJs do *before* outreach (EPK creation, demo curation) and *after* booking (contract review, rider management, payment tracking)?\
- Willingness-to-pay audit: "If NoxReach also handled [adjacent job], would you pay more? How much more?"\
- Integration demand check: "What tools do you wish NoxReach connected to?" (Spotify, SoundCloud, Instagram, Stripe, Calendly)\
\
**Commercial impact**: If you discover DJs want contract + payment management, you expand the product \'97 and the pricing tier \'97 accordingly.\
\
> *Source insight*: "The best CRM for DJs in 2026 isn't just about a contact list; it's about an integrated platform that handles your entire booking lifecycle."\
